node.text:
Good afternoon #BlueAngels fans. This past weekend we had the privilege to perform over the skies of London, Ontario, Canada at #airshowlondon. It was also the first official demonstration of our new C-130J Super Hercules, affectionately known as "Fat Albert." Thank you to the people of London, Ontario for being such wonderful hosts. 

#USNavy #USMC #Airshows #Aviation #FlyNavy

node.text:
Good Morning Fargo! We’re here in North Dakota for the @fargoairsho and this is a very special weekend for us! This is the hometown of our very own Cmdr. Brian Kesselring, commanding officer and flight leader of the Blue Angels! Cmdr. Kesselring graduated from Fargo South High School in 1995, and then went on to graduate from Concordia College in 2000. The entire team is honored to represent the Navy and Marine Corps in Cmdr. Kesselring’s hometown. Come out and see us this weekend July 24-25th at the Hector International Airport!

#BlueAngels #USNavy #USMC #FlyNavy

node.title: Cmdr. Kesselring flies over his hometown!

Good Afternoon #BlueAngels fans! 

A member of our C-130J maintenance team reenlisted today in the United States Marine Corps! 

Please join us in congratulating SSgt. Aaron Fryer of Dearborn, Michigan. Aaron was reenlisted by Maj. Rick Rose, the Blue Angels’ C-130J lead demo pilot.

Aaron has served for 8 years and is currently a part of the Fat Albert Maintenance Team. His work center maintains the airframe, life support, engine, hydraulic and avionics systems of the Blue Angels’ C-130J Super Hercules aircraft.

Congratulations! 

#USNavy #USMC #FlyNavy

“I've always admired the Blue Angels since the start of my military career. I never thought it would be possible to make the team, so being a part of all of this now is just an honor.”

- Marine Corps Sergeant Zachary Parsons, Grayson, Kentucky.

Parsons is a member of the Blue Angels' Fat Albert maintenance team. The Fat Albert Maintenance work center maintains the airframe, life support, engine, hydraulic and avionics systems of the Blue Angels C-130J Super Hercules aircraft, Fat Albert.

Additional photos are from Parson’s time serving in the Marine Corps.

Sgt. Zachary Parsons, currently serving with the Blue Angels flight demonstration team, was awarded the Navy and Marine Corps Medal for his actions which directly resulted in the saving of three lives. The medal is the sea services' highest award for acts of heroism that didn't involve conflict with an enemy force. Sgt. Parsons was presented the award by the Blue Angels commanding officer and flight lead, Capt. Brian Kesselring, in front of the squadron and his family.
	On May 26th, 2019, two North Carolina parents came face-to-face with one of the worst things imaginable for any mother or father. The family of five, wanting to take advantage of the beautiful weather, decided to spend the day at the beach. Unaware of the dangerous high surf and rip current, the three children found themselves pulled almost 150 meters from the shore line. Running to help the children, the father found himself overwhelmed by the surf and called for help.
	Sgt. Parsons, who had been spending the day at the beach, heard the father’s call and immediately jumped into action. He directed his wife to call 911 and made his way to the shore line. Parsons grabbed a nearby boogie board and without hesitation began making his way to the children. With the help of one other bystander, he began shuttling the children back to safety and into the arms of emergency services, who arrived shortly after. 
 	Sgt. Parsons’ heroism that day serves as a testament to the deep-rooted desire to serve and protect that represent the core values of the United States Military. Today, Parsons serves with the C-130J maintenance team, ensuring the Blue Angels’ Super Hercules is mission ready and prepared for its fast paced work environment.

"When I was young I always saw the blue angels as role models. Being a part of the team I’ve met so many great people who’ve helped me become a better person and I hope to be able to use that to inspire others in the future."

- Aviation Electronics Technician 2nd Class Tyler Cutts, Dothan, Alabama.

Cutts is a member of the Blue Angels' avionics team. Navy Aviation Electronics technicians and Aviation Electricians, as well as Marine Corps F/A-18 aircraft electrical systems technicians and squadron aircraft communications/navigation radar systems technicians comprise the Avionics work center. They are responsible for the performance of scheduled and unscheduled maintenance and timely troubleshooting of F/A-18 and C-130 electronic flight controls, communication, navigation, radar, mission computers, display systems and fuel quantity.

Additional photos are from Cutts' time in the Navy.

node.text:
Good afternoon #BlueAngels fans. This past weekend we had the privilege to perform over the skies of London, Ontario, Canada at #airshowlondon. It was also the first official demonstration of our new C-130J Super Hercules, affectionately known as "Fat Albert." Thank you to the people of London, Ontario for being such wonderful hosts. 

#USNavy #USMC #Airshows #Aviation #FlyNavy
